name "chap:Gain-control"

\end_inset

Olfactory receptor neurons use gain control and complementary kinetics to
 encode intermittent odorant stimuli 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Odor landscapes that insects navigate are often not smooth gradients 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Carde:2008fc,Riffell:2008hp"

\end_inset

.
 Instead, turbulent airflows shape odor plumes into intermittent whiffs
 randomly separated by periods of background air (blanks).
 In the absence of reliable spatial gradients, navigating insects may use
 the timing of whiff encounters 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Vergassola:2007dj"

\end_inset

, combined with other sensory modalities such as mechanosensation to detect
 wind direction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Budick:2006ea,Carde:2008fc,Duistermars:2009du"

\end_inset

, to navigate odor plumes towards mates and food.
 Insect olfactory systems face dual challenges in detecting natural odor
 plumes.
 First, the intensity of whiffs is typically distributed according to a
 power law 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Murlis:1992kp"

\end_inset

, with intense whiffs interleaved unpredictably with weak ones 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Riffell:2008hp"

\end_inset

.
 This requires the insect to represent a very large domain of stimulus intensity
 using a relatively narrow response range of its sensors.
 Second, whiff durations and blank durations are also distributed as a power
 law over a wide range of time scales 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Celani:2014ea"

\end_inset

.
 This lack of characteristic scale in the intensity and timing of whiffs
 makes it challenging to precisely detect and encode individual odor whiffs.
 The encoding problem is aggravated by shifting local statistics of odor
 encounters, which change with wind speed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nagel:2011jj,Nagel:2016bl"

\end_inset

, position 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Justus:2002da"

\end_inset

, or environment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Murlis:2000kk"

\end_inset

.
 How does the olfactory system manage to encode whiffs of odors whose intensitie
s and timing can vary over such wide ranges? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several features of the olfactory system contribute to encoding odor stimuli
 of different intensities.
 A single odorant can be detected by multiple receptor types, with different
 sensitivities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hallem:2006iu"

\end_inset

 and static compressive nonlinearities at both 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acf{ORN}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and their post-synaptic targets, the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acf{PN}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, selectively amplify weak signals and suppress responses to large signals
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "deBruyne:2001ur,Bhandawat:2007ie"

\end_inset

.
 Glomerular mechanisms implement a type of divisive gain control that maintains
 PN sensitivity within the range of changing ORN responses 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bhandawat:2007ie,Olsen:2010dc,Olsen:2008kv,Luo:2010fb"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, transduction currents in response to odor pulses scale inversely
 with the intensity of the background signal, consistent with the Weber-Fechner
 Law 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cao:2016jl"

\end_inset

.
 However, whether ORN firing follows a similar scaling is unclear 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cafaro:2016ed,Martelli:2013it"

\end_inset

.
 Thus, although the input-output curve of ORNs to odor stimuli changes with
 odor background, the precise scaling of ORN gain control from stimulus
 to firing rate has not been characterized.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Olfactory responses in insects can be fast.
 Transduction can be initiated within milliseconds of odor reaching the
 antenna 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Szyszka:2014in"

\end_inset

.
 The speed of the response is enhanced by ORN spike generation, which emphasizes
 changes in transduction currents 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nagel:2011jj"

\end_inset

, and by PNs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kim:2015dm"

\end_inset

, which maintain fast information transmission from ORNs to PNs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nagel:2014ee,Raccuglia:2016eu"

\end_inset

.
 In contrast, adaptation to high intensity stimuli slows down transduction
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nagel:2011jj,Cao:2016jl,Kaissling:1987gva"

\end_inset

, a property that might make it difficult to reliably encode the timing
 of odor encounters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We investigated in vivo how 
\emph on
Drosophila
\emph default
 ORNs encode encounters with naturalistic odor plumes, which possess the
 dual complication that both whiff intensities and whiff timing are broadly
 distributed.
 To address this question, we first developed an odorant delivery system
 that reproducibly delivered odorants with naturalistic statistics, or approxima
tely Gaussian statistics with controlled means and variances.
 We simultaneously recorded the odorant stimulus (using a fast 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acf{PID}
\end_layout

\end_inset

) and recorded extracellularly from identified ORNs.
 In these studies, we focused on the phenomenology of odorant encoding,
 which can help to constrain the potential molecular mechanisms that implement
 them.
 We found that in response to naturalistic stimuli, ORNs employed front-end
 nonlinearities inherent in receptor saturation to encode broadly distributed
 signals.
 In addition, ORNs could rapidly desensitize following encounters with odorant
 whiffs, dynamically adjusting gain while responding to intermittent odorant
 stimuli.
 On increasing the mean stimulus background, ORNs decreased gain inversely
 with stimulus intensity, consistent with the Weber-Fechner Law.
 This phenomenon could be explained if the disassociation constant 
\emph on
K
\emph default
 of odorant binding scaled with the mean stimulus intensity.
 Supporting this model, we found that gain control to changes in mean was
 localized to LFP signals, suggesting that adaptation occurs at transduction
 in the ORNs, with little contribution from spiking machinery.
 ORN gain also changed in response to changes in stimulus variance, with
 gain changes distributed equally across transduction and spiking.
 Even though the transduction response time slowed down with increasing
 stimulus intensity, the spiking machinery sped up to compensate.
 The result of these complementary kinetic changes was that the firing rate
 response time remained invariant with stimulus intensity, revealing a mechanism
 that could allow ORNs to preserve information about the precise timing
 of odor encounters over a wide range of rapidly changing signal intensities.
 
\end_layout

