\begin_layout Subsection
Modularity of gain control at transduction and spiking 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since spiking occurs downstream of transduction, Weber-Fechner gain scaling
 at transduction ensures that fluctuations in the input to the spiking machinery
 occur at the same scale, independent of the scale of the stimulus.
 Can spiking gain change to amplify or suppress transduction responses?
 To decouple the overall drive to the neuron from Weber-Fechner gain control
 at transduction, we expressed Chrimson channels 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Klapoetke:2014ja"

\end_inset

 in ab3A ORNs and activated them using red light.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we used a fluctuating ethyl acetate stimulus to probe transduction
 and ORN gain while increasing the neuron’s firing rate using increasing
 backgrounds of red light (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:chrimson"

\end_inset

a-b).
 While increasing light levels elicited increasing firing rates (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:chrimson"

\end_inset

b inset), ORN and transduction gain did not vary with the intensity of supplemen
tal light (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:chrimson"

\end_inset

a-b).
 This suggests that constitutive spiking activity does not feed back onto
 LFP adaptation, or overall ORN gain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, we used a fluctuating light stimulus to probe the spiking gain while
 stimulating the ORN and its receptors with increasing backgrounds of ethyl
 acetate odorant (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:chrimson"

\end_inset

c-d).
 While ethyl acetate backgrounds of increasing intensity increased ORN firing
 rate (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:chrimson"

\end_inset

d inset), they failed to change gain in the spiking machinery.
 Increasing odor backgrounds moved input-output curves along the y-axis
 (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:chrimson"

\end_inset

c), consistent with increasing firing due to background odor, but failed
 to change the slope of these curves, suggesting that ORN gain to the fluctuatin
g light probe was not changed.
 This suggests that adaptation at transduction does not affect gain of the
 spiking machinery, consistent with our result that increasing odor backgrounds
 decreased gain at transduction, but not spiking (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:modularity"

\end_inset

a-d).
