\begin_layout Subsection
The Weber-Fechner Law in olfaction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Weber-Fechner Law has been observed in several sensory systems, including
 vision 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Laughlin:1978go,Burkhardt:1994tt,Nikonov:2006dq"

\end_inset

, audition 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Riesz:1928fx"

\end_inset

, and somatosensation
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Holway:1936ib"

\end_inset

.
 However, a clear identification of the law in the firing rate of ORNs has
 remained elusive, due to difficulties in controlling and measuring odor
 stimuli in gas phase simultaneously with ORN firing rate 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cafaro:2016ed,Martelli:2013it"

\end_inset

.
 Here we directly measured ORN firing rate and stimulus intensity and found
 that the ORN firing rate exhibited Weber-Fechner gain scaling relative
 to the mean stimulus intensity for five different odor-receptor combinations
 (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:weber-law"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:weber-law-supp"

\end_inset

).
 These data suggest that olfaction shares the Weber-Fechner Law with other
 sensory systems.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is the purpose of front-end Weber-Fechner gain scaling? ORNs are capable
 of spiking up to ~300Hz 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hallem:2006iu"

\end_inset

; however, we found that with their compressive gain control, ORNs maintained
 firing rates between 0 - 50 Hz to fluctuating odor stimuli, even with a
 ten-fold increase in the mean stimulus.
 The ORNs’ postsynaptic partners, the projection neurons (PNs) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Olsen:2010dc"

\end_inset

, are most sensitive to ORN firing rates of below ~50 Hz 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Jeanne:2015di"

\end_inset

.
 Thus, gain scaling at ORNs could act to maintain ORN firing rates in the
 range that PNs are most sensitive to for a wide range of concentrations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Variance gain control in olfaction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In principle, gain control in sensory systems could be affected by several
 moments of the stimulus distribution, measured over many timescales.
 In the visual system, gain control depends on stimulus mean and variance,
 but not strongly on higher moments like the skew and the kurtosis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bonin:2006ct,Tkacik:2014fk"

\end_inset

.
 Cell-intrinsic variance gain control exists in a variety of systems, including
 the retina 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zaghloul:2005ir,Beaudoin:2008kk"

\end_inset

, lateral geniculate nucleus 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lesica:2007fd"

\end_inset

, auditory neurons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nagel:2006co"

\end_inset

, and cortex 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DiazQuesada:2008is,Ringach:2007gy"

\end_inset

.
 Photoreceptors do not exhibit variance gain control, and variance adaptation
 arises only in the subsequent processing in bipolar cells and ganglion
 cells 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rieke:JgM-LOjK,Kim:2001vq,Baccus:2002fy"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What could be the functional role of variance gain control in olfaction?
 One possibility is to ensure that ORN responses occupy their full dynamic
 range 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Laughlin:1981wn"

\end_inset

.
 While we quantified our stimulus in terms of the first and second moments
 of the stimulus statistics in this study, these moments may not map simply
 onto the salient features that are most relevant to the fly’s encoding
 scheme.
 Variance gain control could therefore be a consequence of an adaptive represent
ation that is important to the coding properties of the ORN.
 Nonetheless, because i) variance gain control is distributed between transducti
on and spiking machinery (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:modularity"

\end_inset

), ii) mean gain control is linked to calcium influx and variance gain control
 is not (Figs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:calcium-mean"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:calcium-variance"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cao:2016jl"

\end_inset

, and iii) mean gain control slows down transduction (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:kinetics"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cao:2016jl,Nagel:2011jj"

\end_inset

 but variance gain control does not (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:kinetics-variance"

\end_inset

), adaptation to the stimulus variance is mechanistically distinct from
 adaptation to stimulus mean.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Models and mechanisms of ORN response and gain control 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results presented here, and the models that reproduce them, focus on
 the phenomenology of gain control in ORNs.
 Do these phenomenological results constrain possible mechanisms that could
 implement gain control in ORNs? Weber-Fechner gain scaling (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:weber-law"

\end_inset

) can be reproduced by models using feed-forward loops 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Clark:2013bk,Goentoro:2009dj"

\end_inset

, integral feedback 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Huang:2000di"

\end_inset

 or both 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schulze:2015bt"

\end_inset

.
 A detailed biophysical model of odor-receptor binding and channel opening
 has been proposed to account for transduction responses to odors 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nagel:2011jj"

\end_inset

.
 While this model can change gain via a negative feedback mechanism, it
 does not reproduce the Weber-Fechner law, or the slowdown of LFP kinetics
 upon adaptation.
 Here we showed that these features emerge if we assume that: (i) the activity
 a of the Or-Orco complex feeds back onto the free energy difference between
 the active and inactive state of the unbound Or-Orco complex, which in
 turns affects both the rates of activation and inactivation of the complex;
 (ii) the rate at which is modified only depends on the activity a.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such an architecture reproduces the Weber-Fechner law and is similar to
 that of the bacterial chemotaxis system 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Barkai:1997vj"

\end_inset

.
 There, adaptation is mediated by two antagonistic factors, one that acts
 on inactive complexes only, and another one that acts on active complexes
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Barkai:1997vj"

\end_inset

.
 While the molecular architecture of the signaling pathway in ORNs has not
 been fully characterized, several studies have implicated calcium as a
 slow diffusible factor that could mediate adaptation to the mean stimulus
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Deshpande:2000vt,Stortkuhl:1999vl"

\end_inset

.
 Decreasing extracellular calcium levels, or internal free calcium breaks
 Weber-Fechner gain scaling at transduction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cao:2016jl"

\end_inset

 and increasing stimulus amplitude leads to increasing levels of intracellular
 calcium (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:calcium-mean"

\end_inset

).
 Other mechanisms have also been implicated in adaptation of ORNs, like
 auto-regulation of 
