\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Invariant firing rate kinetics could improve odor-guided flight behavior
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Insects follow odor plumes to their source to find food or reproductive
 mates 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Murlis:1992kp"

\end_inset

.
 For flies, this task is challenging since they fly fast (~30 cm/s) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tammero:2002wd"

\end_inset

 and odor filaments are narrow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Murlis:1992kp"

\end_inset

.
 Even for relative broad and static odor plumes, flies are within odor plumes
 so briefly that they experience plume contact and plume loss in quick successio
n (10-250 ms) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vanBreugel:2014is"

\end_inset

.
 Olfactory search behavior in this setting consists of rapid flight surges
 on encountering odor plumes, and stereotyped crosswind casts on losing
 odor plumes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vanBreugel:2014is"

\end_inset

.
 Navigation based on odor intensities alone may not be possible, as odor
 intensities are not informative about the direction to the odor source
 at length scales longer than 10 cm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Murlis:1992kp"

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, there is a growing body of evidence underlining the importance
 of timing in olfaction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Smear:2011ez,Smear:2013iq,Shusterman:2011cp,Martelli:2013it,Rebello:2014ba"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this context, it may be important for the fly to know precisely when
 it encountered an odor filament.
 This task is made difficult by the fact that olfactory adaptation to large
 stimuli slows transduction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cao:2016jl,Nagel:2011jj"

\end_inset

.
 Adaptation could change the kinetics of the transduction from whiff to
 whiff, so that downstream neurons would have to know the adaptation state
 of the ORN to precisely determine encounter timing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our results reveal that flies solve this problem by using transduction and
 firing machinery that possess complementary kinetic properties.
 This maintains ORN firing rate lags at a constant value in the face of
 slowing transduction.
 Our results suggest that ORNs can encode the precise timing of odor encounters,
 for a wide range of odor concentrations.
 Such an encoding scheme could aid insects in navigating odor plumes to
 their source.
 
\end_layout

