\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:variance-supp"

\end_inset

b-c).
 A single filter was used to project stimuli in both low- and high-variance
 epochs; changes in gain from low- to high-variance stimuli thus appear
 solely in the nonlinearity (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:variance-supp"

\end_inset

d).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Measuring lags.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all our data, we measured the stimulus together with the response of
 ORNs.
 This allowed us to estimate transduction and firing lags with respect to
 the stimulus.
 In general, we estimated response lags by computing cross-correlation functions
 from the stimulus to the response.
 Lag was defined to be the location of the peak of the cross-correlation
 function.
 (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:kinetics"

\end_inset

a-b).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Estimation of variance gain control timescale.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate the timescale of variance gain control (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:variance"

\end_inset

), we computed input-output curves from the projected stimulus to the firing
 rate in 50 ms bins, pooling all trials together.
 This allowed us to estimate gain in 50 ms bins, together with the stimulus
 contrast (standard deviation/mean).
 We plotted time series of instantaneous gain and stimulus contrast (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:variance"

\end_inset

h), and observed that while the stimulus contrast changed rapidly after
 the switch from high to low variance (at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=5$
\end_inset

 s), the instantaneous gain changed more slowly, but still changed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim130$
\end_inset

 ms, suggesting that timescale of variance gain control is relatively rapid.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Statistical tests.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To determine if ab3A transduction-to-firing gain varied with the mean stimulus
 (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:modularity"

\end_inset

d), we used a Spearman rank correlation test.
 To determine if gains varied significantly from low to high variance epochs
 (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:variance"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:modularity"

\end_inset

), we first reshaped the raw data into trials 10 s long.
 Each trial consisted of a high variance epoch followed by a low variance
 epoch.
 Each trial was fit with three linear models, and yielded three pairs of
 gains, for transduction gain, firing gain, and total ORN gain.
 We discarded all trials where any linear model fit was poorly correlated
 with data, retaining only trials where all fits had high correlations with
 data (
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}>0.8$
\end_inset

, see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:variance-supp"

\end_inset

f-g).
 We used the Wilcoxon signed rank test on these tuples to determine if the
 difference in gains in the low and high variance epochs was statistically
 significant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modelling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Stimulus binding and the activity of the Or-Orco complexes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that Or and Orco form a complex that can exist in two conformations
 that can bind ligand.
 The concentration of unbound active complexes is C* and that of unbound
 inactive one is C.
 The corresponding concentrations for the bound complexes are C*S and CS
 (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:lfp-model"

\end_inset

a).
 The fraction of active Or-Orco complexes is therefore:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=\frac{C*+C*S}{C+CS+C*+C*S}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Un)binding of odorant is taken to be much faster than the (in)activation.
 Thus, the probability to be bound in the active and inactive cases are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{flalign*}
{} & P_{b}=\frac{S}{S+K_{\textrm{off}}}\\
{} & P_{b}*=\frac{S}{S+K_{\textrm{on}}}
\end{flalign*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\textrm{on}}<K_{\textrm{off}}$
\end_inset

 are the dissociation constants for each state.
 Let the free energy difference in units of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}T$
\end_inset

 between the active and inactive states be 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{b}$
\end_inset

 when unbound and when bound, respectively.
 For simplicity, we assume detailed balance (this can easily be relaxed
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Skoge:2013fq"

\end_inset

), which constrains the free energy difference between 
\emph on
C*S
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
CS
\emph default
 to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{b}=\varepsilon+\log(K_{\textrm{on}}/K_{\textrm{off}})$
\end_inset

.
 The activation kinetics can then be described by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dC*}{dt}=w_{+}^{u}C-w_{-}^{u}C*
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the rates are 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{\pm}^{u}=\frac{\alpha}{1+e^{\pm\varepsilon}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{\pm}^{b}=\frac{\alpha}{1+e^{\pm\varepsilon^{b}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We constrained the energy barrier between the active and inactive conformations
 by making the simplifying assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{+}^{u}+w_{-}^{u}=\alpha=w_{-}^{b}+w_{-}^{b}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is an intrinsic switching rate (see e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Skoge:2013fq"

\end_inset

).
 From these considerations we can then derive Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lfp-model-a"

\end_inset

 from the main text, which describes the dynamics of the activity: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{da}{dt}=(1-a)w_{+}(S,ε)-aw_{-}(S,ε)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with the rates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{+}(S,ε)=P_{b}w_{+}^{b}+(1-P_{b})w_{+}^{u}=\frac{S}{S+K_{\textrm{off}}}\frac{α}{1+e^{\varepsilon+\log(\frac{K_{\textrm{on}}}{K_{\textrm{off}}})}}+\frac{K_{\textrm{off}}}{S+K_{\textrm{off}}}\frac{α}{1+e^{\varepsilon}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{-}(S,ε)=P_{b}^{*}w_{-}^{b}+(1-P_{b}^{*})w_{-}^{u}=\frac{S}{S+K_{\textrm{on}}}\frac{α}{1+e^{-\varepsilon-\log(\frac{K_{\textrm{on}}}{K_{\textrm{off}}})}}+\frac{K_{\textrm{on}}}{S+K_{\textrm{on}}}\frac{α}{1+e^{-\varepsilon}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a steady state signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, the activity relaxes towards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{a}(S,\varepsilon)=\frac{1}{1+\frac{w_{-}}{w_{+}}}=\frac{1}{1+e^{\varepsilon(\frac{1+S/K_{\textrm{off}}}{1+S/K_{\textrm{on}}})}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where the overbar indicates that equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lfp-model-a"

\end_inset

 is solved at steady state.
 We model adaptation assuming that the activity feeds back onto the free
 energy difference with rates that depend only on the activity (the effective
 switching rate is constant): 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dε/dt=β(a-a_{0})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is the rate of adaptation.
 Note that the free energy is bounded both from below and from above.
 In practice, we only need the lower bound 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{L}<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 At steady state (for values of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 high enough that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{L}<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

) we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{a}=a_{0}$
\end_inset

which implies that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{\varepsilon}(S)=\log(\frac{1-a_{0}}{a_{0}}\frac{1+S/K_{\textrm{on}}}{1+S/K_{\textrm{off}}})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, at steady state, adaptation causes the free energy difference of the
 complex to increase with the logarithm of the background signal intensity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Kinetic slowdown upon adaptation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\varepsilon}(S)$
\end_inset

 into the definitions of the (in)activation rates, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{w_{+}}(S)=\frac{S}{S+K_{\textrm{off}}}\frac{\alpha}{1+\frac{K_{\textrm{on}}}{K_{\textrm{off}}}\frac{1-a_{0}}{a_{0}}\frac{1+S/K_{\textrm{on}}}{1+S/K_{\textrm{off}}}}+\frac{K_{\textrm{on}}}{S+K_{\textrm{off}}}\frac{\alpha}{1+\frac{1-a_{0}}{a_{0}}\frac{1+S/K_{\textrm{on}}}{1+S/K_{\textrm{off}}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{w_{-}}(S)=\bar{w_{+}}(S)\frac{1-a_{0}}{a_{0}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\textrm{on}}<K_{\textrm{off}}$
\end_inset

, the rates and are decreasing functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 in the range 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0\leq S\leq\sqrt{\frac{1-a_{0}}{a_{0}}K_{\textrm{on}}K_{\textrm{off}}}
\]

\end_inset

In our case this bound is large (~40 V) and in our experiments the rates
 are decreasing functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 over the entire range.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Receptor activity to LFP.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The output of the model described above is a time series of the fraction
 of receptors that are active, .
 Receptor activation can lead to the opening of other channels, which results
 in a transduction current that we measure as changes in the LFP.
 To generate LFP responses from this, we use 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{LFP}=C_{0}(K_{LFP}\text{\otimes}a(t))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\otimes$
\end_inset

 represents a convolution and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{LFP}$
\end_inset

 is a linear time-invariant monolobed filter that is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{LFP}=\frac{t^{m}e^{\nicefrac{-t}{\tau}}}{m!\tau^{m+1}}\theta(t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Receptor activation to firing rates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since firing rates cannot be negative, and since the LFP to spiking transformati
on has been shown the partly differentiating 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nagel:2011jj"

\end_inset

, we generated firing rate responses from the receptor activity using 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{F}=N(K_{F}\otimes a(t))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is an output nonlinearity which is a simple threshold linear function (
\begin_inset Formula $N(x<0)=0$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $N(x>0)=Cx$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\otimes$
\end_inset

 represents a convolution and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{F}$
\end_inset

 is a linear time-invariant filter that is given by the sum of two other
 kernels: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{F}=K_{1}+\alpha K_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where each kernel is parameterized by a Gamma function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
K_{i}=\frac{t^{m}e^{\nicefrac{-t}{\tau_{i}}}}{m!\tau_{i}^{m+1}}\theta(t) & i\in\{1,2\}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

